<HEAD>Zumwalt Backs Compensation for Vets With Agent Orange-Related
Illness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam veterans who suffered cancer and other
diseases after exposure to Agent Orange should receive disability
payments, says a government adviser who had ordered spraying of the
herbicide.
   Retired Adm. <PERSON>Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr.</PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION>Department of Veterans
Affairs</ORGANIZATION> advisory panel that he believed 27 cases of illness, mostly
cancers, could be sufficiently linked to Agent Orange exposure to
justify compensation.
   Zumwalt spoke to the <ORGANIZATION>Environmental Hazards Advisory Committee</ORGANIZATION> as
its newest member and as a personal adviser to Veterans Secretary
<PERSON>Edward J. Derwinski Jr</PERSON>.
   The committee on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> began reviewing scientific evidence
on the health effects of Agent Orange.
   Zumwalt speaks from a unique perspective: as commander of naval
forces in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>, he ordered the spraying of the
dioxin-contaminated herbicide, which was used to deny jungle cover
to the enemy.
   In addition, <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON>'s son, who served in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>, died of a
cancer linked to Agent Orange exposure, and a grandson has birth
defects linked to exposure.
   Zumwalt urged the panel to take a fresh look at the scientific
evidence on Agent Orange. He also said a study he conducted for
<PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON> parallels the work of an independent group of scientists
hired by three veterans' groups.
   That group, the <ORGANIZATION>Agent Orange Task Force</ORGANIZATION>, said this month there
was enough evidence to justify compensation for eight diseases or
ailments that have been linked to exposure. The panel said there
were 13 other health problems, mostly cancers, for which there is
sound evidence of connection but not yet enough evidence to justify
compensation.
   ``I suggest to you that any objective review by knowledgeable
experts in the field would predictably lead to much the same
conclusion,'' <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> said. He contended the <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION> panel lcked a
systematic approach or epidemiological perspective.
   Zumwalt went further, saying he believes 27 ailments, mostly
cancers, could be compensated using VA criteria that were adopted
as the result of a court order last year.
   The main diseases cited by the task force, <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> and others
are non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, <ORGANIZATION>Hodgkin</ORGANIZATION>'s disease, soft tissue sarcoma,
chloracne and other skin disorders, liver disorders, a metabolic
disorder known as porphyria cutanea tarda and birth defects.
   Zumwalt's list includes 13 kinds of cancer in addition to those
already cited.
   The <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION> has said it will come up with final rules this year on
compensation. Derwinski must make the decision based on the
recommendations of the 15-member advisory committee, a panel of
scientists and lay people.
   The <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION> decided in <DATE>March</DATE> to award compensation for 1,800 <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>
veterans with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. That decision was based on a
<ORGANIZATION>Centers for Disease Control</ORGANIZATION> study that found an increased risk of
the disease among <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans as a whole. The study was
inconclusive on Agent Orange exposure.
   About 36,000 claimants have been denied compensation despite
their contention that Agent Orange exposure caused their health
problems. About 240,000 say they have been exposed to the herbicide.
   The Zumwalt statement heartened congressional Vietnam-era
veterans who have pushed for legislation to award compensation.
   ``The evidence is there,'' said <PERSON>Sen. Tom Daschle</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-S.D.</LOCATION> ``The
only question left is whether or not the federal government is
willing to accept its responsibility.''
</TEXT>
