<HEAD>Report Criticizes VA's Refusal to Compensate Agent Orange-Related
Illness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A report to Veterans Secretary <PERSON>Edward J.
Derwinski</PERSON> sharply criticizes the government for its longstanding
refusal to compensate <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans for illnesses linked to
Agent Orange exposure.
   The report by Admiral <PERSON>Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr.</PERSON> was released the same
day an advisory panel to the <ORGANIZATION>Department of Veterans Affairs</ORGANIZATION> paved
the way for compensation to <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans suffering from a rare
cancer known as soft-tissue sarcoma.
   Derwinski is expected to decide in late <DATE>May</DATE> or early <DATE>June</DATE>
whether to award compensation for that form of cancer.
   ``I hope this is the beginning of the end of the nightmare Agent
Orange victims have suffered,'' said <PERSON>Sen. Thomas A. Daschle</PERSON>,
<LOCATION>D-S.D.</LOCATION>, a co-chair of the Vietnam-Era Veterans in <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> caucus.
   The <ORGANIZATION>VA Advisory Committee on Environmental Hazards</ORGANIZATION> made its
recommendation <DATE>Thursday</DATE> after reviewing scientific studies on the
connection between dioxin and herbicide exposure to soft tissue
sarcoma.
   Zumwalt, one of four lay members of the 15-member panel,
criticized the committee <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> for its previous handling of the
Agent Orange question. The panel was created by <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1984</DATE> to
investigate the link between exposure and a host of ailments,
largely cancers, that <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans have been complaining about
since the <DATE>1970s</DATE>.
   A federal court order last year, which <PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON> declined to
appeal, forced the panel to begin its work anew. Although the last
<ORGANIZATION>Agent Orange</ORGANIZATION> was sprayed in <DATE>1971</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION> has awarded only a handful
of Agent Orange claims, and those were all for a skin condition
called chloracne.
   Derwinski decided in <DATE>March</DATE> that all <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans with
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma should be compensated.
   The <ORGANIZATION>American Legion</ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> Veterans of <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> and outside
scientists commissioned by the two groups have long criticized the
government's refusal to acknowledge health hazards associated with
<ORGANIZATION>Agent Orange</ORGANIZATION>. The herbicide was contaminated with dioxin, labeled a
``probable human carcinogen'' by the <ORGANIZATION>Environmental Protection
Agency</ORGANIZATION>.
   On <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION> released a report that <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> compiled for
<PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON>.
   ``Were the faulty conclusions, flawed methodology and noticeable
bias of the advisory committee an isolated problem, correcting the
misdirection would be more manageable,'' <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> wrote.
   ``But, experience with other governmental agencies responsible
for specifically analyzing and studying the effects of exposure to
Agent Orange strongly hints at a discernible pattern, if not
outright governmental collaboration, to deny compensation to
<LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans associated with exposure to dioxin,'' he wrote.
   Zumwalt referred to the <ORGANIZATION>federal Centers for Disease Control</ORGANIZATION>,
given responsibility by <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> for conducting Agent Orange
studies because of ``evidence of VA's footdragging.''
   Zumwalt repeated allegations raised in a congressional hearing
last <DATE>summer</DATE> that <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> sabotaged its Agent Orange study, suggesting
``that political pressures once again interfered with the kind of
professional, unbiased review <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> had sought to obtain.''
   Compensation for <ORGANIZATION>Agent Orange</ORGANIZATION> will cost nearly <MONEY>$90 million</MONEY> for
only a few of the ailments linked to the herbicide, the
<ORGANIZATION>Congressional Budget Office</ORGANIZATION> says.
   <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> has maintained it cannot establish who among <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>
veterans was exposed to Agent Orange, making further study
impossible.
   <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> said his own review of the scientific evidence suggests
28 ailments, mostly cancers, can be linked to Agent Orange exposure.
   Zumwalt, commander of naval forces in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>, ordered the
spraying of the defoliant in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> and lost a son, a <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>
veteran, to a cancer linked to Agent Orange exposure. Zumwalt has
said he nonetheless would have ordered the spraying because it
ultimately saved more lives than it cost.
   <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> said the herbicide was used in undiluted form to remove
enemy cover, destroy enemy crops and clear vegetation around
military installations, landing zones, fire base camps and trails.
   He said more was sprayed than records indicate, because of
unofficial uses of the herbicide.
</TEXT>
