<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-90 1710EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-AgentOrange     05-17 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agent Orange,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zumwalt Says Much More Defoliant Sprayed Than Recorded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More Agent Orange was sprayed in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> than
official records show, a former commander said in a report <DATE>Thursday</DATE>
that also suggests ``a discernible pattern, if not collaboration,''
to deny veterans compensation.
   Also, a <ORGANIZATION>Veterans Affairs Department</ORGANIZATION> panel issued a ruling that
brings compensation closer to veterans exposed to the herbicide who
suffer from soft-tissue sarcoma, a rare cancer.
   Admiral <PERSON>Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr.</PERSON>, in his report to Veterans Secretary
<PERSON>Edward J. Derwinski</PERSON>, said he was certain from his experience that
more Agent Orange was spread than recorded.
   ``Combat units ... frequently conducted `unofficial' sprayings
of Agent Orange obtained from out of channel, and thus unrecorded
sources.'' said <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON>.
   ``Additionally, as commander, <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Naval Forces, <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>, I was
aware that <ORGANIZATION>Agent Orange</ORGANIZATION> issued to Allied forces was frequently used
on unrecorded missions,'' <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> said in the report.
   The report, issued <DATE>May 6</DATE>, was released <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, a day after
<PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> told an advisory panel to the VA he believes that 28
diseases are linked to Agent Orange exposure. Zumwalt, a special
adviser to <PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON>, was recently named to the department's
<ORGANIZATION>Advisory Committee on Environmental Hazards</ORGANIZATION>.
   The panel on <DATE>Thursday</DATE> determined it is as likely as not that a
significant association exists between soft-tissue sarcoma and
Agent Orange exposure.
   Derwinski is to decide by <DATE>June</DATE> whether to award disability
payments to veterans with that disease. Derwinski decided in <DATE>March</DATE>
that all <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma should be
compensated.
   The advisory committee in <DATE>August</DATE> will examine studies relating
dioxin and herbicide exposure to a skin disease known as chloracne,
and a metabolic disorder known as porphyrea cutanea tarda.
   The two reports make it likely that veterans will be compensated
for soft-tissue sarcoma. VA spokesman <ORGANIZATION>Bonner Day</ORGANIZATION> said the
department had no figure on how many Agent Orange claimants said
they have soft-tissue sarcoma.
   Zumwalt's report said the herbicide was used in strengths far in
excess of that suggested by the manufacturers. The makers have
settled a class-action lawsuit brought by afflicted veterans.
   He also criticizes government actions and studies on Agent
Orange, including the activities of the advisory panel.
   His broadsides backed up claims by veterans who have been trying
to get compensation for more than a decade and who claim the
government has had to be pushed to move and has ignored evidence
supporting links between Agent Orange and cancers.
   ``Were the faulty conclusions, faulty methodology and noticeable
bias of the advisory committee an isolated problem, correcting the
misdirection would be more manageable,'' <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> wrote.
   ``But, experience with other governmental agencies responsible
for ... analyzing and studying the effects of exposure to Agent
Orange strongly hints at a discernible pattern, if not outright
governmental collaboration, to deny compensation to <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>
veterans for disabilities associated with exposure to dioxin.''
   Committee chairman <PERSON>Oliver Meadows</PERSON> said he would not comment on
the Zumwalt report.
   Zumwalt ordered the spraying of the defoliant in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> and
lost a son, a <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veteran, to a cancer linked to Agent Orange
exposure.
   About 12 million gallons of the herbicide, which contained
cancer-causing dioxin, was sprayed from <DATE>1965</DATE> to <DATE>1970</DATE>, according to
records.
   <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> said, however, ``a significant, if not major source of
exposure was from non-recorded, non-Ranch Hand operations.'' Ranch
Hand was the name for the aircraft spraying operation.
   ``Evidence readily suggests that at the time experts knew that
Agent Orange was harmful to military personnel,'' he said.
   <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> said that in addition to removing enemy cover and
destroying crops, the herbicide was sprayed to clear vegetation
around military installations, landing zones, fire base camps and
trails.
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900330-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-90 0309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CDC-Veterans     03-30 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC-Veterans,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>VA Compensation Decision Doesn't Resolve Agent Orange Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decision by the <ORGANIZATION>Veterans Affairs
Department</ORGANIZATION> to award compensation to <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans suffering from
one rare form of cancer doesn't resolve the dispute over exposure
to Agent Orange.
   The decision, announced <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, could make it possible for the
VA to close the doors to compensation for a host of ailments linked
to the herbicide used in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> from <DATE>1965</DATE> to <DATE>1970</DATE> to deny jungle
cover to the enemy.
   Based on a study released the same day by the federal <ORGANIZATION>Centers
for Disease Control</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON>Edward J. Derwinski</PERSON>
said he would award 100 percent disability payments to any <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>
veteran suffering from non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
   Payments would be retroactive, and widows and children would
receive survivors' benefits as well. More than 1,800 veterans or
their survivors could receive compensation as a result, according
to <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION> data, at a cost of <MONEY>$23 million</MONEY> the first year and about <MONEY>$25
million</MONEY> in subsequent years.
   Veterans advocates were pleased with the immediate decision but
remained skeptical about the study's application to the larger
Agent Orange questions. The government has insisted there is no
scientific proof of a link between the herbicide and a host of
ailments, mostly cancers.
   ``When the study was designed, <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> admitted that the study
population was significantly diluted with unexposed veterans, that
it lacked a meaningful measure of exposure and that it lacked the
statistical power to detect anything less than a <PERCENT>100 percent</PERCENT>
increase in certain cancers,'' said <PERSON>Sen. Thomas A. Daschle</PERSON>.
   <PERSON>Daschle</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-S.D.</LOCATION>, is co-chairman of the Vietnam-Era Veterans in
<ORGANIZATION>Congress Caucus</ORGANIZATION> and wrote legislation to make the disease and
others suspected of having a link with <ORGANIZATION>Agent Orange</ORGANIZATION> exposure
service-connected.
   The <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> ``Selected Cancers Study'' looked at the occurrence of
cancer in all <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans in relation to men who did not serve
in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>. Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma was the only cancer found in the
study to have had an unusually high incidence.
   Derwinski was initially very careful to say his decision was not
an Agent Orange decision, but he and his aides were fuzzier in
later remarks.
   Derwinski at one point said he made his determination based at
least in part on the work of a VA-commissioned panel of outside
scientists. That group reported <DATE>last November</DATE> that it could not
find, but neither could it rule out, a statistically significant
association between Agent Orange exposure and non-Hodgkin's
lymphoma.
   As a result of that finding, <PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON> had said he would
postpone a decision on Agent Orange compensation until after the
<ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> study. He had planned, however, to wait for the advisory
panel's recommendation in <DATE>May</DATE>.
   Derwinski jumped the gun <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, but he insisted the panel
would continue its work on the Agent Orange issue. Derwinski is
also consulting with <PERSON>Elmo Zumwalt</PERSON>, the retired admiral who ordered
Agent Orange spraying and whose son died of a cancer linked to
exposure.
   Some 36,000 Agent Orange claims have been made for the lymphoma
and other ailments have been made, and almost all have been
rejected. About 230,000 veterans have asserted they have been
exposed to Agent Orange.
   The <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> study left some questions unresolved. It noted, for
example, that <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> veterans were more inclined to get the disease
even though they were least likely to have been exposed to Agent
Orange. It also said the lowest incidence was among veterans of <ORGANIZATION>III
Corps</ORGANIZATION>, the area of highest Agent Orange use.
   <PERSON>John Hanson</PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION>American Legion</ORGANIZATION> official, said the study
neglected to point out that the <ORGANIZATION>III Corps</ORGANIZATION> area included <LOCATION>Saigon</LOCATION>,
which wasn't sprayed.
   Deputy Veterans Secretary <PERSON>Anthony J. Principi</PERSON> said VA was making
the presumption that any veteran who served in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> was exposed
to Agent Orange. But <PERSON>Hanson</PERSON> said such a determination dilutes any
statistical sample to the point where an Agent Orange determination
is impossible.
</TEXT>
