<FIRST>r w AM-AgentOrange     06-26 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agent Orange,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Testify That Weedkillers May be More Harmful Than
Thought</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Garry in 7th graf and Shelia in 10th graf are cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers and homeowners frequently use
weedkillers that contain a key ingredient of Agent Orange that may
be more harmful than previously thought, scientists told a
congressional panel <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   ``It appears to me that there are other contaminants in
herbicides, as well as herbicides per se, which have not been
adequately evaluated for carcinogenicity in animals let alone
studied for their effect ... in humans,'' <PERSON>Daniel Thau Teitelbaum</PERSON>, a
<LOCATION>Denver</LOCATION> physician, told a <ORGANIZATION>House Government Operations</ORGANIZATION> subcommittee.
   Teitelbaum studied industry records as part of the class-action
lawsuit by <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans against the makers of Agent Orange.
   In the 20 years of controversy surrounding whether the
government should pay benefits to ailing <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans who were
exposed to Agent Orange, attention has focused on dioxin
contamination 2,4,5-T _ one of the herbicide's two key ingredients.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Environmental Protection Agency</ORGANIZATION> has labeled dioxin a
``probable human carcinogen'' and 2,4,5-T has been out of
circulation for years.
   But scientists told the subcommittee that the other key
ingredient _ 2,4-D _ causes cancers and other ailments linked to
Agent Orange. Evidence shows that 2,4-D was also contaminated with
harmful compounds, some related to dioxin, according to testimony
on the government handling of Agent Orange research.
   The farm-chemical industry says ongoing research into 2,4-D is
needed but that the ``weight of the evidence'' so far indicates the
risk of harm is relatively small if it does indeed exist, industry
spokesman <PERSON>Garry Hamlin</PERSON> said in a telephone interview from
<LOCATION>Indianapolis</LOCATION>.
   A so-called phenoxy herbicide, 2,4-D is sold over the counter to
kill dandelions and other lawn weeds. Farmers use it against weeds
in corn, wheat, rice and sorghum.
   Teitelbaum, noting that use of 2,4,5-T was first discontinued
because of concern about birth defects, said studies were needed on
possible birth defects resulting from 2,4-D exposure.
   Two <ORGANIZATION>National Cancer Institute</ORGANIZATION> studies have shown an increased
risk of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, a rare cancer, in ``frequent users
of agriculture chemicals,'' said <ORGANIZATION>NCI</ORGANIZATION> researcher <PERSON>Shelia Hoar Zahm</PERSON>.
   The studies of farm workers in <LOCATION>Kansas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Nebraska</LOCATION> found that
the risk grows or drops according to skin exposure and how soon
after exposure the worker changed clothes.
   Vietnam veterans were exposed to Agent Orange in concentrations
far in excess of the normal strength, special adviser <PERSON>Elmo R.
Zumwalt Jr.</PERSON> has told the <ORGANIZATION>Veterans Affairs Department</ORGANIZATION>.
   The department said this year it would compensate veterans for
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and for another rare cancer _ soft tissue
sarcoma. However, the government maintains that exposure can't be
documented.
   Zumwalt, a retired admiral, ordered Agent Orange sprayed in
<LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> to clear dense jungle. His son, who served in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>,
later died of cancer, which <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> attributes to Agent Orange. he
said 27 ailments can be linked to Agent Orange.
   Zumwalt, appearing before the subcommittee on human resources
and intergovernmental relations, reiterated his contention that
government and industry officials ``intentionally manipulated or
withheld compelling information on the adverse health effects
associated with exposure to the toxic contaminants contained in
Agent Orange.''
   In a related matter, Rep. <PERSON>Ted R. Weiss</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-N.Y.</LOCATION>, said his
subcommittee had forced the <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> to release a 4-year-old draft
report showing an increase of birth defects among the offspring of
those who handled and sprayed Agent Orange from the air.
   <PERSON>Patti Turner</PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION>Air Force Surgeon General</ORGANIZATION>'s
office, said the conclusions were premature.
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 0050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AgentOrange Bjt   10-30 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agent Orange, Bjt,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veterans' Administration to Reconsider Agent Orange Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advisory committee to the <ORGANIZATION>Department of
Veterans Affairs</ORGANIZATION> this week may open the door a crack to disability
benefits for <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans exposed to Agent Orange.
   Responding to a federal court decision in <DATE>May</DATE>, the 15-member
Veterans' <ORGANIZATION>Advisory Committee on Environmental Hazards</ORGANIZATION> will look
again at scientific papers and studies on the herbicide used to
clear dense foliage that hid the enemy.
   This time, however, the committee will use standards considered
less strict than those used for determining other service-connected
disabilities.
   No one is predicting the outcome. But there is agreement that VA
Secretary <PERSON>Edward J. Derwinski</PERSON> wants to resolve the issue quickly
and in favor of veterans.
   ``I don't think he's going to fool around very long,'' <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION>
spokesman <PERSON>Don Smith</PERSON> said. ``He's so far exhibited a degree of
willingness _ if not impatience _ to go along rather rapidly with
this.''
   Once the committee does its work <PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON> is ``kind of on his
own as to how he wants to fly on this,'' <PERSON>Smith</PERSON> said. He said
<PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON> will make a final determination on the committee's
recommendations within two weeks of receiving results of the
meeting.
   According to one congressional source, <PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON>'s actions mean
``he's almost promised people'' that he will take some positive
action for veterans.
   Veterans blame exposure to Agent Orange for cancers, skin
diseases and genetic damage leading to miscarriages or birth
defects. The committee will spend its first two days reviewing
about 20 or 30 studies on the connection between exposure and
non-Hodgkins lymphoma, one of the most frequently cited cancers,
then study other diseases at later meetings.
   On <DATE>Friday</DATE>, it will issue recommendations on non-Hodgkins
lymphoma and Agent Orange.
   The four-year-old advisory committee and government scientists
have thus far rejected a link between Agent Orange exposure and
health problems other than a skin condition known as chloracne.
   The <ORGANIZATION>American Legion</ORGANIZATION>, the prime veterans' group in this dispute,
contends the committee has a longstanding bias against veterans.
   Not so, says <PERSON>Oliver Meadows</PERSON>, the disabled veteran and scientific
layman in charge of the panel. ``Their greatest interest is their
own integrity as scientists,'' he said.
   The government says the main problem with studies up to now is
that there has been no way to verify exposure to dioxin. The
<ORGANIZATION>American Legion</ORGANIZATION> and others say the government has detailed records
on spraying activities that can be combined with equally detailed
records on troop movements.
   Agent Orange, an orange-brown liquid that was shipped in
orange-striped barrels, was sprayed in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> from <DATE>January 1965</DATE> to
<DATE>April 1970</DATE>. More than 230,000 veterans have registered with VA
claiming to have been exposed. More than 36,000 veterans have filed
for disability benefits claiming Agent Orange exposure caused their
problems, and two have been granted compensation _ for chloracne.
   Agent Orange is suspect because it contains ``phenoxy''
herbicides associated with certain cancers as well as dioxin, which
has been found to cause cancer in laboratory animals.
   Dioxin's links to human health problems are disputed, although
its links to human birth defects are more firmly established.
   A ruling in <DATE>May</DATE> by <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> District <PERSON>Judge Thelton E. Henderson</PERSON> in
<LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> created a way out of the impasse over <ORGANIZATION>Agent Orange</ORGANIZATION>. A
new administration and the elevation of the Veterans'
Administration to cabinet status added another ingredient.
   Henderson ruled <DATE>May 2</DATE> that the VA imposed an ``impermissibly
demanding test'' for linking Agent Orange with health problems.
   Although the <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION> has relied on a ``cause and effect''
relationship in determining service-connected disabilities, the
committee was to use a different standard: ``a significant
statistical association.''
   Derwinski told Attorney General <PERSON>Richard L. Thornburgh</PERSON> on <DATE>May 8</DATE>
that he had decided against an appeal.
   New regulations for reviewing studies using the new standard,
effective <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, say a link will be deemed to exist if the
studies associating Agent Orange with health problems outweigh the
evidence that there is no association.
   The regulations say the <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION> secretary can give the ``benefit of
the doubt to the conclusion that the association exists.''
   In early <DATE>October</DATE>, <PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON> named Adm. <PERSON>Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr.</PERSON> as a
special adviser with a specific emphasis on Agent Orange.
   Zumwalt ordered spraying of Agent Orange during <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>, and he
lost a son who served in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> to a cancer linked with that
spraying. Zumwalt is known as a veterans' advocate on this issue.
</TEXT>
