<FIRST>r w PM-AgentOrange     08-03 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agent Orange,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agent Orange Compensation Back in Federal Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dispute over compensating <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans
for a host of cancers and other ailments believed to be linked to
Agent Orange exposure is back in federal court.
   In a lawsuit filed here <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, two veterans groups asked that
federal scientists be forced to complete a study on the health
effects of Agent Orange on <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans and their children.
   The suit said the <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> administration ordered the study
canceled in <DATE>1987</DATE>, four years after it began, because of concerns
that civilian claims against government and industry would follow a
decision to compensate veterans.
   The suit was filed in <ORGANIZATION>U.S. District Court</ORGANIZATION> by the <ORGANIZATION>American
Legion</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> Veterans of <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>, five individual veterans and
four surviving spouses.
   It said that without the study, mandated by <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1979</DATE>, it
is impossible to persuade the <ORGANIZATION>Veterans Affairs Department</ORGANIZATION> to award
disability and death payments to thousands of veterans who were
exposed to the dioxin-contaminated defoliant.
   The herbicide, used to destroy ground cover and crops, has been
blamed by veterans groups for 19 cancers and a variety of other
health problems, including birth defects.
   The VA this year decided to award compensation for two rare
cancers: soft-tissue sarcoma and non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
   The soft-tissue sarcoma decision was based on the
recommendations of an advisory panel acting under a court order to
reconsider the scientific evidence. The lymphoma decision was based
on a <ORGANIZATION>Centers for Disease Control</ORGANIZATION> study of <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans that
only indirectly looked at Agent Orange exposure.
   Veterans Secretary <PERSON>Edward J. Derwinski</PERSON> said the lawsuit will set
back his effort to resolve the Agent Orange dispute. He began that
effort shortly after he took office by deciding not to appeal a <DATE>May
1989</DATE> federal court ruling that VA standards on Agent Orange
disability claims were too strict.
   The ruling in <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> came as a result of a lawsuit filed
by the <ORGANIZATION>Vietnam Veterans of America</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``Now, these organizations have acted to return to the courtroom
with litigation aimed at forcing the scientific conclusions they
want,'' <PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON> said. ``Their suit impugns the integrity of
respected scientists at the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Centers for Disease Control</ORGANIZATION> whose
work thus far has added much to what we know about the health of
<LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans.''
   The <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION>, in canceling the study, said there was no
scientifically valid way to document who was exposed. The American
Legion and independent scientists say records of troop movements
can be matched with spraying records to find the likely exposed
veterans.
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC>
