<HEAD>CDC Finds `No Evidence' of Vet Cancer Link to Agent Orange</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS three grafs after 12th, `The Veterans...', to UPDATE
with veterans secretary saying compensation would be paid to
veterans suffering from non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. Picks up 13th graf,
`American Legion...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Centers for Disease Control</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>today</DATE> its
long-awaited study of Agent Orange shows <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans at
increased risk of only one type of cancer _ and ``no evidence''
that the risk stems from exposure to the dangerous herbicide used
in the war.
   The study, which had been criticized by veterans groups even
before it was released, focused on <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans and cancer, and
``only indirectly evaluated Agent Orange exposure,'' the <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> said.
   But it added that the cancer risk among the vets in the study
``seemed to be the opposite of the pattern for use of Agent
Orange.'' Veterans who served on <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> ships were somewhat more
likely to get cancer than those who served on land, and veterans
who served in the region of heaviest Agent Orange use were at
``somewhat lower risk'' than others, the <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> said.
   Agent Orange, sprayed by the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military to remove jungle and
crops in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>, contained dioxin, a highly toxic chemical that
some studies have found to increase the risk of cancer.
   The <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> study, conducted over five years, surveyed male cancer
patients who were the right age to have served in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>, whether
they did serve or not. They were compared with a group of similar
males with no history of cancer.
   The patients' medical records were examined for six kinds of
cancer, including soft tissue cancer and similar sarcomas, a group
of cancers which the <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> concedes has been ``of great concern among
<LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans.''
   Vietnam vets were found to be at a roughly <PERCENT>50 percent</PERCENT> increased
risk for non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, a ``relatively rare'' cancer of
the lymphatic system, the <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> said.
   ``The study did not find any evidence that the increased risk
might be due to Agent Orange exposure,'' said <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON>William
L. Roper</PERSON>.
   There was ``no evidence,'' the <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> reported, ``that
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma was more likely to develop in one group of
<LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans than in another.''
   Specifically, the yearly risk of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma is about
one in 10,000 for men 35 to 59, the age group of most <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> vets.
The risk for <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> vets is about 1.5 per 10,000, <PERSON>Roper</PERSON> said.
   But the <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> found ``no increased risk'' for sarcomas, usually
cancers of the body's connective tissues, or for other cancer types.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Veterans Administration</ORGANIZATION> has been awaiting the study before
making its decision on whether to award benefits to veterans
exposed to Agent Orange. Nearly 35,000 claims have been filed
citing the chemical as a cause of disabilities, including cancer,
skin disease and miscarriages by veterans' wives.
   Veterans Secretary <PERSON>Edward J. Derwinski</PERSON> said <DATE>today</DATE> that based on
the study he would order compensation paid to veterans suffering
from non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
   Derwinski, in announcing the move in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, mentioned only
the link between <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> service and the lymphoma. He did not say
the connection was because of Agent Orange.
   His announcement speeds up VA action on the findings; the agency
had said it would submit the study to a review panel.
   American Legion officials told their <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veteran members in
advance of today's announcement that they should not be too
optimistic about this study, which was mandated by <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``The government has ducked the issue of Agent Orange for more
than a dozen years,'' said the legion's national commander, <ORGANIZATION>Miles
S. Epling</ORGANIZATION>. ``We are tired of waiting for more studies, especially
irrelevant ones.''
   The legion has accused <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> of ignoring military records that
could have produced a more detailed study.
   The <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> study found that the risk of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma was
nearly double _ <PERCENT>90 percent</PERCENT> higher _ for <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> veterans stationed on
ocean ships than for non-veterans. That was the only statistically
significant risk for any branch of service, said <PERSON>Dr. Daniel A.
Hoffman</PERSON>, assistant director for science at the <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Center for
Environmental Health</ORGANIZATION>.
   For all veterans, the <PERCENT>50 percent</PERCENT> higher risk of that type of
cancer is what epidemiologists call ``a weak association,'' <PERSON>Hoffman</PERSON>
said. While statistically significant, ``anything less than a
twofold increase can sometimes be caused by other factors,'' he
said.
   The <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> study did not suggest reasons for the increased risk for
one cancer over another, or for the increased risk among <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION>
sailors at sea.
   The study did not include blood tests to determine the actual
amount of dioxin that might remain in the cancer patients'
bloodstream two decades or more after military service.
   <PERSON>Hoffman</PERSON> said such tests were not a practical way to determine
dioxin exposure because it is possible that test findings might be
tainted by the patients' illness itself.
</TEXT>
