<HEAD>Zumwalt Named to VA Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adm. <PERSON>Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr.</PERSON>, whose son died of
cancer after being exposed to Agent Orange that his father had
ordered sprayed in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>, has been named a senior adviser to
Veterans Affairs Secretary <PERSON>Edward J. Derwinski</PERSON>, the department said
<DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   The appointment of <LOCATION>Zumwalt</LOCATION>, 68, is one of several steps the <ORGANIZATION>VA
department</ORGANIZATION> has taken under <PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON> to address the concerns of
veterans who have health problems that they say are linked to
exposure to the defoliant.
   The <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> will counsel on a variety of issues, but
``the first on the agenda will be Agent Orange.''
   <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON>, who retired as chief of naval operations in <DATE>1974</DATE>, was
commander of in-country naval forces in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> in the <DATE>late 1960s</DATE>,
when Agent Orange was sprayed in the <ORGANIZATION>Mekong Delta</ORGANIZATION>.
   His son, <PERSON>Elmo R. Zumwalt III</PERSON>, had served as a patrol boat
commander at the same time. He died in <DATE>August 1988</DATE> of a form of
cancer linked to Agent Orange exposure. He was 42.
   A grandson, <PERSON>Elmo Russell Zumwalt IV</PERSON>, suffers from a congenital
dysfunction of his physical senses. Agent Orange has also been
blamed for birth defects.
   The father has said he still would have ordered spraying the
defoliant because overall casualties were reduced.
   The two co-wrote a book, ``My Father, My Son,'' about the
experience. It was later made into a television movie.
   On <DATE>Monday</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>VA Department</ORGANIZATION> published regulations creating
less-stringent guidelines for determining whether there is a link
between Agent Orange exposure and a host of ailments. A <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION> panel
will re-examine studies in <DATE>November</DATE> in light of the new guidelines.
   Government scientists have said there is no way of determining a
positive link, a position challenged by veterans groups and outside
scientists. The <ORGANIZATION>American Legion</ORGANIZATION>, for example, has released a major
study showing that exposure is related to benign fatty tumors,
adult acne, skin rash with blisters, several other ailments and an
increased risk of miscarriages in wives of veterans.
   Although the study said it couldn't determine a link with cancer
because the sample was too small, the legion said the methodology
proved such a study could be made.
   The new regulations allow for a link to be established if
studies ``permit the conclusion that it is at least as likely as
not that the purported relationship between a particular type of
exposure and a specific adverse health effect exists.''
   Some 35,000 veterans have filed Agent Orange claims, but only
five have been allowed because of the policy that no firm
connection exists. More than 230,000 veterans have reported their
exposure to the <LOCATION>VA</LOCATION>. About 2.6 million personnel served within the
borders of <LOCATION>South Vietnam</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
