<HEAD>Secretary Derwinski Delays Agent Orange Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veterans' Affairs Secretary <PERSON>Edward Derwinski</PERSON>
says he won't decide before <DATE>March</DATE> whether to grant disability
payments to <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans exposed to Agent Orange.
   <PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON> said <DATE>Friday</DATE> he won't make his decision until the
<ORGANIZATION>Centers for Disease Control</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION> releases the results of a
study begun in <DATE>1985</DATE>. The study is expected in <DATE>March</DATE>.
   After a <DATE>Nov. 3</DATE> advisory committee meeting, <PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON> had
promised a decision in a few weeks.
   <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> epidemiologists in <DATE>1985</DATE> launched a major study of the health
records of thousands of veterans to see if they were at increased
risk of five types of cancer: lymphoma, soft-tissue sarcoma, and
nasal, nasopharyngeal and liver cancer.
   The advisory committee said after reviewing more than 30 studies
that it could not find a statistically significant relationship
between a rare cancer, non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, and exposure to the
chemicals used in the defoliant Agent Orange.
   In <DATE>May</DATE>, a federal judge in <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> ruled that the
department had been too strict in denying disability benefits on
the grounds there was no proof that those chemicals caused the
illnesses cited by some 34,000 veterans.
   Instead, the judge said the department need only find
statistically significant associations between exposure and
illness. Derwinski decided not to appeal the decision.
   <PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON> said in a statement <DATE>Friday</DATE> that several committee
members had said the <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> study could weigh heavily in their
recommendations.
   ``I am as determined now to resolve this issue as I was when I
decided not to appeal the court decision, but it is logical to wait
for a few extra months for the results of the <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> cancer study,''
he said.
   Agent Orange, used in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> to strip vegetation cover used by
guerrillas, has been blamed by veterans' groups for many disorders,
particularly cancer, because it was contaminated with dioxins, a
byproduct of its manufacture.
   Some of the 75 dioxin compounds are among the most powerful
causes of cancer ever tested in laboratory animals, but it has
never been proven they can cause cancer in humans.
   Exposure to dioxin in high concentrations is known to cause
chloracne, a skin disorder, and recent work has led some scientists
to suspect dioxin may also cause birth defects.
   In <DATE>1986</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> required the Veterans Administration to give
hospital care to any veteran exposed to Agent Orange in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>
unless the VA found some other cause for his disability.
</TEXT>
