<HEAD>Florida Vets Start Agent Orange Survey</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TD4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans group in <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>
said <DATE>Monday</DATE> it has lost patience with federal government efforts to
study the effects of <ORGANIZATION>Agent Orange</ORGANIZATION> and will conduct its own survey
on exposure to the toxic defoliant.
   ``This state - the <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans of <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> - have said
enough is enough,'' said <PERSON>David Kaufman</PERSON>, a veteran from <LOCATION>Fort
Lauderdale</LOCATION>. ``We're going to take the bull by the horns.''
   <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>, with about 527,000 <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans, is the first state
to attempt such a project, according to <PERSON>Kaufman</PERSON>, chairman of the
<ORGANIZATION>Agent Orange Committee</ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION>Vietnam Veterans of Florida</LOCATION>.
   The survey has the backing of national <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans groups
and individual scientists at the <ORGANIZATION>Department for Veterans Affairs</ORGANIZATION>,
the <ORGANIZATION>Environmental Protection Agency</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Centers for Disease
Control</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Kaufman</PERSON> said.
   ``There are scientists and epidemiolgists who work for the VA
and the <ORGANIZATION>EPA</ORGANIZATION> who are outraged at this latest <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> fiasco,'' <PERSON>Kaufman</PERSON>
told reporters.
   A congressional study released last month charged that the <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION>
misspent <MONEY>$6.6 million</MONEY> while conducting a disputed study of the
effects of Agent Orange.
   An estimated 12 million gallons of Agent Orange, composed
primarily of cancer-causing dioxin, was sprayed over <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> by
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> troops between <DATE>1965</DATE> and <DATE>1970</DATE> to destroy the jungle that hid
the enemy.
   Veterans groups say exposure to Agent Orange has been linked to
19 types of cancer and other health problems, including birth
defects. Earlier this year, the <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION> decided to award compensation to
veterans with two rare cancers, soft-tissue sarcoma and
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, linked to Agent Orange.
   Since <DATE>1981</DATE>, some lower-income veterans who believe their health
problems are caused by Agent Orange have received VA care, the <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION>
said.
   But the veterans are a long way from getting the government to
acknowledge that Agent Orange has caused lingering diseases in
veterans and birth defects in their children, veterans groups say.
   The <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> has said that military records did not identify veterans
who had been exposed to the chemical.
   ``We're going to provide them with information,'' <PERSON>Kaufman</PERSON> said.
   He said there are 116 scientists from the <ORGANIZATION>VA</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>EPA</ORGANIZATION> ``who
have pledged that if we get them the surveys they will go through
them.'' Those scientists, whom <PERSON>Kaufman</PERSON> would not name, also helped
write the 116-question survey, he said.
   The organization has printed only 1,000 surveys thus far. It
wants to get 500,000 distributed and returned within six months.
<PERSON>Kaufman</PERSON> said it will cost about <MONEY>$3 million</MONEY> to conduct the survey,
and that veterans would have to raise money as they go to pay for
the project.
   About 200 surveys were handed out <DATE>Monday</DATE> to veterans gathered
for Veterans Day ceremonies at the group's <LOCATION>Tallahassee</LOCATION>
headquarters, <PERSON>Kaufman</PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
