<HEAD>Atwater Released From Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican National Chairman <PERSON>Lee Atwater</PERSON> is
home from the hospital after physicians adjusted the medication he
is taking for a brain tumor, an aide said.
   Atwater, 39, was released <DATE>Sunday</DATE> after undergoing a radiation
treatment the day before at <ORGANIZATION>George Washington University Hospital</ORGANIZATION>,
said <PERSON>Leslie Goodman</PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION>Republican National
Committee</ORGANIZATION>. He had been admitted on <DATE>Friday</DATE> complaining of
queasiness, she said.
   ``He's home and is in good spirits again,'' <PERSON>Ms. Goodman</PERSON> said
<DATE>Sunday</DATE>. ``He said he was feeling fine.''
   A small, non-malignant tumor was discovered earlier this month
on the right side of Atwater's brain after he collapsed during a
speech. He is taking radiation treatments five days a week to
reduce the tumor.
   Atwater was named head of the <ORGANIZATION>RNC</ORGANIZATION> after managing <PERSON>George Bush</PERSON>'s
presidential campaign in <DATE>1988</DATE>.
</TEXT>
