   Elmo <PERSON>R. Zumwalt III</PERSON>, who died of
cancer two decades after his father ordered use of Agent Orange in
<LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>, once swam through water doused with the defoliant to
collect weapons from <ORGANIZATION>Viet Cong</ORGANIZATION> boats.
   He won over his crew, but that swim may have marked the
beginning of his last battle, with the cancer that ended his life
<DATE>Saturday</DATE> at age 42.
   Retired Adm. <PERSON>Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr.</PERSON>, the American naval commander
in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> who ordered the spraying of the defoliant then thought
to be harmless, said his son's death will only push him to work
harder to force the government to compensate veterans who suffered
from <ORGANIZATION>Agent Orange</ORGANIZATION>'s effects.
   ``There are still many hundreds of veterans who do need help,''
<PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> said the day his son died. ``I believe very strongly now
that the evidence is clear that the Agent Orange is responsible for
the problems many veterans are having.''
   His son was diagnosed in <DATE>1983</DATE> as having non-Hodgkins lymphoma.
Two years later, doctors found he had lymphoma <PERSON>Hodgkins</PERSON> disease.
   His son, <PERSON>Elmo Russell Zumwalt IV</PERSON>, suffers from a congenital
dysfunction that confuses his physical senses.
   The Zumwalts chronicled their battle with cancer in <DATE>1986</DATE> with
the book, ``My Father, My Son,'' which they wrote with author <PERSON>John
Pekkanen</PERSON>. The book was made into a television movie in <DATE>May</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> said his son was strong until the end, even joking and
teasing with relatives during <DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>evening</TIME>. He died in his sleep
<DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>morning</TIME>.
   ``I do not second guess the decisions Dad made in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>, nor
do I doubt for a minute that the saving of human life was always
his first priority in his conduct of the war,'' the younger <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON>
once said. ``I have the greatest love and admiration for him as a
man, and the deepest respect for him as a military leader.''
   Zumwalt was commanding a swift boat along the rivers of the Ca
<PERSON>Mau Peninsula</PERSON> when his father, the youngest man ever to serve as
chief of naval operations, ordered the spraying of Agent Orange to
save servicemen from being killed by enemy ambushes along the
waterways.
   Before the spraying, <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> forces had a <PERCENT>6 percent</PERCENT> casualty rate
each month. Afterward, that figure dropped to less than <PERCENT>1 percent</PERCENT>.
   Since the war, the elder <PERSON>Zumwalt</PERSON> and his son had pushed for
government assistance to veterans affected by Agent Orange.
   On <DATE>June 30</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> removed the last legal
obstacle to a <MONEY>$180 million</MONEY> settlement between <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans and
the manufacturers of Agent Orange. The justices let stand rulings
that dismissed lawsuits by about 300 veterans who had challenged a
<DATE>1984</DATE> settlement.
