<HEAD>Senators Optimistic About Agent Orange Benefits Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators advocating disability benefits for
<LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans suffering from cancer they believe caused by <ORGANIZATION>Agent
Orange</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>Thursday</DATE> they were confident of finally winning
congressional passage after repeated setbacks.
   Sen. <PERSON>John F. Kerry</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-Mass.</LOCATION>, said the compromise bill would
provide interim disability benefits to veterans who were exposed to
the chemical defoliant during the <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> War and now suffer from
either non-Hodgkin's lymphoma or soft-tissue sarcoma.
   Under the bill, disability benefits would extend only through
<DATE>1993</DATE>. Survivors' benefits for spouses would go through <DATE>mid-April
1992</DATE>. <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION>, which by then would have received a new study by the
<ORGANIZATION>Centers for Disease Control</ORGANIZATION>, would have to vote to continue the
benefits.
   The measure is needed ``not only to help veterans with their
medical difficulties, but it is also important as a statement that
we intend to make good on our promises to help those who fought in
the war,'' said <PERSON>Kerry</PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> lieutenant who piloted a patrol
boat in the <ORGANIZATION>Mekong Delta</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``Too many veterans remember what it was like to fight the VC
(<ORGANIZATION>Viet Cong</ORGANIZATION>) They didn't have to come back here to fight the VA
(<ORGANIZATION>Veterans Administration</ORGANIZATION>, the name still used for the Veterans
Department),'' the senator said.
   Separate Agent Orange bills sponsored by <PERSON>Kerry</PERSON> and <PERSON>Sen. Thomas
Daschle</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-S.D.</LOCATION>, failed in <DATE>1987</DATE> and again last year. The <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>
administration steadfastly opposed the proposals, saying more
scientific evidence was needed to link the chemical defoliant used
by <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> forces in <LOCATION>Southeast Asia</LOCATION> to the cancers in the light of
several studies that failed to find such a link.
   But <PERSON>Kerry</PERSON> and <PERSON>Daschle</PERSON>, at a news conference introducing the
legislation, said positive signs from both the new administration
and Capitol Hill account for their optimism.
   The senators said they were encouraged by Veterans Affairs
Secretary <PERSON>Ed Derwinski</PERSON> and his decision last month not to appeal a
federal appeals court's decision striking down regulations to
restrict compensation for Agent Orange victims.
   Derwinski also ordered reviews of the cases of all <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>
veterans whose Agent Orange claims were denied. <PERSON>Daschle</PERSON> praised
<PERSON>Derwinski</PERSON> as the ``most sympathetic'' head of the <ORGANIZATION>Veterans
Administration</ORGANIZATION> since the <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> War.
   The bill's prospects improved when <PERSON>Sen. Alan Cranston</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-Calif.</LOCATION>,
chairman of the <ORGANIZATION>Senate Veterans' Affairs</ORGANIZATION>, backed it late last year
after various changes to narrow its scope.
   The measure would cost an estimated <MONEY>$19 million</MONEY> annually in
benefits, <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> aides said.
</TEXT>
