<HEAD>Most Vietnam Vets Escaped Heavy Exposure to Dioxin, Study Suggests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veterans group criticized a new report by the
federal <ORGANIZATION>Centers for Disease Control</ORGANIZATION> that suggests most <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> GIs
escaped heavy exposure to the poison dioxin, unless they handled
the herbicide Agent Orange.
   ``This study seems to be pretty much the same data that was
released a year ago, only a year ago it was portrayed rather
differently,'' said <PERSON>Barry Kasinitz</PERSON>, a spokesman for the
35,000-member <ORGANIZATION>Vietnam Veterans of America</ORGANIZATION>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> last year concluded that exposure to dioxin could not be
determined using military records of troop locations and spraying
of Agent Orange, which contained the deadly poison.
   ``Now ... they are jumping to the conclusion that very few
people were exposed,'' <PERSON>Kasinitz</PERSON> said <DATE>Thursday</DATE> in a telephone
interview from <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>. ``That was a bit of a jump in logic that
doesn't seem to be substantiated.''
   The <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION>'s new report, in today's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION>American Medical
Association</ORGANIZATION>, describes a comparison of blood tests between 646
<LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans and 97 non-Vietnam veterans.
   ``Current <ORGANIZATION>TCDD</ORGANIZATION> (dioxin) levels were nearly identical in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>
and non-Vietnam veterans,'' the researchers said.
   The latest study deliberately drew <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans from
battalions that had served in areas most heavily sprayed with Agent
Orange around <LOCATION>Saigon</LOCATION> in <DATE>1967</DATE> and <DATE>1968</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>CDC</ORGANIZATION> said.
   Only two <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans, or <PERCENT>0.3 percent</PERCENT> of all 646 tested, had
blood dioxin levels greater than 20 parts per trillion, considered
``clearly elevated,'' the researchers said.
   ``These two men each reported their health status as `excellent'
and did not attribute any health problems to Agent Orange
exposure,'' the researchers added.
   The two men were not among the <PERCENT>14 percent</PERCENT> of the <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>
veterans in the study group who did link health problems to
exposure.
   ``This study is consistent with other studies and suggests that
most <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Army</ORGANIZATION> ground troops who served in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> were not heavily
exposed to <ORGANIZATION>TCDD</ORGANIZATION> (dioxin), except perhaps men whose job involved
handling herbicides,'' the researchers said.
   But <PERSON>Kasinitz</PERSON> said the new report gives the ``unfortunate''
impression that small exposures to dioxin were harmless, which has
not been proven, ``and that there is no need for the government to
act to assist those that have been harmed.''
   Dioxin stays in the bloodstream for many years, and high levels
of the chemical can be measured with blood tests as long as two
decades after someone has been exposed, the researchers said.
   Agent Orange was used as a defoliant in <LOCATION>Southeast Asia</LOCATION> during
the <DATE>1960s</DATE> by the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military. Some <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans contend it
has caused them such health problems as cancer, immune system
disorders and birth defects in their children.
   The <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> just two months ago cleared the last
legal obstacle to a <MONEY>multimillion-dollar</MONEY> settlement that could
benefit up to 250,000 <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> veterans in a class-action lawsuit
against the seven manufacturers of Agent Orange.
   But scientists are still trying to settle a continuing
controversy over exactly what health effects the dioxin in Agent
Orange may have.
   Dioxin is known to be one of the most powerful causes of cancer
in laboratory animals ever tested. It has not been shown to cause
cancer in humans, but the <ORGANIZATION>Environmental Protection Agency</ORGANIZATION>
classifies it as a probable carcinogen.
</TEXT>
